<!-- SECTION 1 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">The scenario shift</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">A three-to-four month timeline changes the analytical question entirely.</h2>

<p class="prose">A CIA assessment delivered to administration policymakers last week concluded that Iran can sustain pressure on the Strait of Hormuz for at least three to four months before facing severe economic hardship. The intelligence community's judgment was more sober than the US administration's public position. The report also found that Tehran retains approximately 70–75% of its pre-conflict missile stockpiles. Iran has begun storing unsold oil aboard tankers, reducing field output to preserve infrastructure, and exploring overland export routes through Central Asia.</p>

<p class="prose">Three to four months is not a spike. It is long enough to exhaust strategic petroleum reserves in most exposed importers, force spot market restructuring, and begin to affect refinery configurations locked to Gulf crude grades. The analytical question shifts from the stress scenario of: "what happens if Hormuz closes?" To: "which importers absorb what costs, across which commodities, for how long?" That is a different question, and it requires bilateral trade data to answer.</p>

<div class="compare-grid">
 <div class="compare-card featured">
  <div class="compare-card-label">Sustained disruption — months</div>
  <div class="compare-card-title">Strategic reserves exhaust. Sourcing decisions must be made.</div>
  <div class="compare-card-body">IEA member states hold roughly 90 days of strategic petroleum reserves in aggregate. A three-to-four month disruption pushes into and potentially through that buffer. The market response can no longer be delay and hope. It must actively restructure supply chains for specific importers toward non-Gulf origins at a cost premium. For LPG, there is no equivalent reserve buffer or alternative supply. <strong>The timeline is the exposure.</strong></div>
 </div>
 <div class="compare-card">
  <div class="compare-card-label">Capacity sensitivity score 1.00</div>
  <div class="compare-card-title">Hormuz has no bypass. Every percentage point of disruption is effective.</div>
  <div class="compare-card-body">Unlike Malacca (sensitivity 0.85, with Lombok and Sunda as partial bypasses), Hormuz carries a capacity sensitivity of 1.00. There is no navigable alternative for laden VLCCs or LNG carriers exiting the Persian Gulf. Every stated percentage of closure translates directly to effective disruption. A 90-day scenario at 100% closure is 90 days of full supply interruption, not 90 × 0.85.</div>
 </div>
</div>

<hr class="section-rule" />

