<div class="callout">
 <div class="callout-label">The Greece number</div>
 <div class="callout-body">Greece is 54.6% dependent on Hormuz for crude petroleum, the highest of any importer in the current 51-nation model. Nations outside model coverage may carry higher figures. The value ($8.5B annual) is smaller than China's, but Greek independent refiners are configured around specific Gulf crude grades and have limited ability to substitute quickly. For P&I underwriters with Greek tanker or refinery clients, this is an acute concentration risk at exactly the moment when the disruption is longest.</div>
</div>

<hr class="section-rule" />

<!-- SECTION 3 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">Two categories of risk</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">Supply substitution at cost, versus structural supply gap. The distinction is not minor.</h2>

<p class="prose">Hormuz is a cul-de-sac. Every loading terminal in the Persian Gulf — Ras Tanura, Ruwais, Basra, the offshore Qatar LPG berths — sits inside the Strait. If Hormuz closes, no vessel carrying Gulf cargo can exit by any alternative maritime route. There is no rerouting Gulf tankers around the Cape of Good Hope. The "rerouting" option in the table above is more precisely supply substitution: the importer finds a non-Gulf source of crude, and the vessel carrying that alternative cargo travels to them by whatever route is available.</p>

<p class="prose">That distinction matters for understanding which importers genuinely benefit from supply alternatives. European importers (France, Germany, and to a lesser degree Greece) have access to Atlantic Basin crude — West Africa, North Sea, Americas — that reaches them directly from the west, with no Cape routing penalty. Asian importers (China, Indonesia, and others) face a different geometry: their nearest large alternative supply base is also the Atlantic Basin, but for a cargo originating in West Africa or the US Gulf Coast, reaching an East Asian port requires sailing around the Cape of Good Hope, adding approximately 13 days versus the normal Gulf baseline. The Cape premium in this analysis is the cost of that substitution voyage, not the cost of rerouting a Gulf tanker.</p>

<p class="prose">Brazil and Canada appear in the crude dependency table with significant percentages (24.0% and 14.5% respectively), but both are major domestic oil producers. Their Gulf crude imports reflect refinery grade preferences and specific configuration requirements rather than structural vulnerability. The mitigation path runs through domestic production ramp-up and grade substitution. Argentina's refined petroleum dependency (19.9%) reflects a domestic refining capacity deficit that has no simple maritime fix.</p>

<div class="callout-verdict">
 <div class="callout-verdict-label">The exposure structure at three to four months</div>
 <div class="callout-verdict-body">At the duration the CIA has assessed, the commercial picture separates into three groups. <strong>European crude importers</strong> (Greece, France, Germany) face a cost burden manageable through Atlantic supply substitution, though at escalating spot prices and with some grade mismatch for Greek refiners. <strong>Asian crude importers</strong> (China, Indonesia and others not yet in the model) face the same supply substitution challenge but pay the Cape routing premium on top: Atlantic crude traveling to East Asia adds roughly 13 days and $1.4 million per VLCC voyage. <strong>LPG importers across Southeast Asia</strong> face the most acute exposure: Gulf LPG is physically trapped, and no alternative source at comparable scale exists.</div>
</div>

<hr class="section-rule" />

<!-- SECTION 4 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">The substitution economics</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">What the Cape routing costs Asian importers, vessel class by vessel class, over a 90-day window.</h2>

<p class="prose">For Asian importers sourcing Atlantic Basin crude as a Gulf substitute, the Cape of Good Hope adds 12 to 16 days depending on vessel class and origin port. At current market rates (VLCC bunker $55,000 per day, charter $45,000 per day), a single VLCC voyage via Cape costs $1.20 million more in direct vessel costs, plus approximately $197,000 in cargo carrying cost at 5% per annum on a representative $120 million cargo. The total is $1.40 million per voyage. European importers accessing Atlantic supply do not bear this premium — their substitute cargo is already pointed in their direction.</p>

