<p class="prose">The $480 million figure is the direct fleet cost of sourcing Atlantic Basin substitute supply via Cape routing over 90 days. It is not the trade value at risk. It is the additional cost imposed on the vessels moving cargo to Asian importers via the alternative route. The trade value disrupted behind those vessel movements is orders of magnitude larger.</p>

<p class="prose">The longer voyage also extends the liability window. Every additional day a laden VLCC spends at sea is an additional day of P&I exposure on an in-transit cargo. For underwriters writing accumulation on Cape-routed substitute supply, the concentration of diverted tanker traffic around southern Africa during a sustained Hormuz disruption creates its own modelling problem.</p>

<hr class="section-rule" />

<!-- SECTION 5 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">The LPG dimension</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">Five Southeast Asian nations carry a Hormuz exposure that headlines have not reached.</h2>

<p class="prose">Coverage of the disruption has focused almost entirely on crude petroleum and LNG. The LPG exposure in Southeast Asia is structurally significant and has received almost no analytical attention. Thailand is 13.6% dependent on Hormuz for LPG; Indonesia adds 8.2% on top of its 14.7% crude exposure; Vietnam stands at 6.7%; the Philippines at 5.7%; Malaysia at 3.4%. These are bilateral figures from Narrows Tier 1 data; real country-pair trade flows, not corridor allocations.</p>

<div class="callout-red">
 <div class="callout-label">LPG is not crude — and there is no alternative Qatar</div>
 <div class="callout-body">LPG (propane and butane) is a distinct commodity from LNG (liquefied natural gas). LPG primarily from Qatar and the UAE flows to Southeast Asian importers aboard purpose-built pressurised LPG carriers. If Hormuz closes, that cargo is physically trapped at the loading terminal. There is no rerouting it. An empty LPG carrier could in principle be redirected to seek alternative LPG supply, but no alternative source at comparable scale exists: US propane is the main non-Gulf export, but it is largely committed to existing contracts and a US-to-Southeast-Asia voyage is extremely long. Australia produces modest LPG volumes associated with its LNG projects, but not at the scale Qatar exports. <strong>A supply shortfall in Thailand or the Philippines is not a cost event. It is a domestic energy access event.</strong> These five nations are the most underanalysed Hormuz exposure in the current coverage.</div>
</div>

<hr class="section-rule" />

<!-- SECTION 6 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">What the bilateral data adds</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">The headline number cannot tell you who pays. The bilateral data can.</h2>

<p class="prose">The figure that circulates in coverage: "20% of global oil supply transits Hormuz" is correct. But who can use that figure to make any structural decision? It does not tell an accumulation underwriter which of their insured counterparties carries the exposure. It does not tell a crude desk what percentage of their specific supply chain is at risk. It does not tell a lender what a 90-day disruption does to voyage economics across their book.</p>

